    <section id="sect-00003">
      <title>Diagnostics</title>
      <para id="para-00012">
        A physical examination by a health care provider with a sphygmomanometer (blood pressure monitor) will identify an elevated blood pressure. A 12-lead ECG (electrocardiogram) can assist in determining if the heart has a normal or abnormal rhythm. Blood work is then obtained to determine factors that contribute to hypertension as well as how the body is reacting to elevated blood pressure. These laboratory tests include a complete blood cell count (CBC), basic electrolyte panel, cholesterol panel, and renal function. An echocardiogram (EKG), an ultrasound of the heart, is not typically included in diagnostic procedures to determine hypertension; however, the healthcare provider may add this diagnostic study to visualize the heart’s chambers, valves, and pumping action. Diagnosis for hypertension is based on the findings of the physical examination and the diagnostic study results.
      </para>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00004">
      <title>Clinical Manifestations</title>
      <para id="para-00013">
        Symptoms of hypertension may not occur for years, and most of the time the symptoms can be silent. Symptoms typically associated with hypertension include elevated blood pressure readings, headaches, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, visual disturbances, and neurological disturbances such as disorientation or a decreased level of consciousness. Over time, uncontrolled hypertension can lead to organ damage, and clients can experience symptoms related to the specific organ that is damaged; for example, with kidney damage the client may experience end stage renal disease (ESRD) and require dialysis.
      </para>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00005">
      <title>Nonpharmacologic Treatment for Hypertension</title>
      <para id="para-00014">
        Nonpharmacologic measures used as treatment for hypertension center around lifestyle changes. Lifestyle changes should focus on the client’s personal, social, and cultural influences. These changes may include diet modification, physical activity and exercise, smoking cessation, alcohol consumption reduction, relaxation techniques, and self-monitoring.
      </para>
      <note class="trending-today" id="note-00002">
        <title>Subtitle</title>
        <para id="para-00015">
          The American Heart Association (AHA) conducted a critical assessment of research and clinical knowledge on cardiovascular disease across the United States specifically addressing women’s health. In its report to the president, <emphasis effect="italics"><link url="https://www.heart.org/en/news/2022/05/09/report-calls-out-gaps-in-womens-heart-disease-research-care">Gaps Identified in Women’s Heart Disease Research and Care</link></emphasis>, gaps were identified and actions outlined to optimize cardiovascular health in women across their lifespan, with the goal of reaching health equity in health care. The AHA has deployed awareness campaigns that are culturally sensitive and focus on the optimization of preventive and clinical care. Community engagement and advocacy in policy change at the legislative level have been encouraged.
        </para>
        <para id="para-00016">
          The Heart Team multimedia series hosted by Jorge Plutzy, MD, Director of Preventive Cardiology at Harvard Medical School, and Michael Farkouh, MD, Director of the Peter Munk Clinical Trials Unit and Vice Chair of Medicine at the University of Toronto, provides <link url="https://www.hcplive.com/view/heart-team-women-cardiovascular-health?seriesVid=1">four podcasts on the current research in women’s cardiovascular health and disparities in practice</link>. Dr. Martha Gulati, MD, Director of Preventive Cardiology, Associate Director of the Barbara Streisand Women’s Heart Center, Associate Director of Preventive and Cardiac Rehabilitation at the Cedar Sinai Medical Center, joins the last two episodes of the multimedia series and discusses improving female participation in research trials and the future of clinical practice for women and cardiovascular diseases.
        </para>
        <para id="para-00017">
          In a fireside video chat, <emphasis effect="italics"><link url="https://youtu.be/XMmBJHDI4eM">The Heart of the Matter: Racial and Gender Bias in Cardiovascular Care</link></emphasis>, presented by Abbott Cardiovascular, an expert panel of health care providers and representatives discusses cardiovascular care. The panel identifies gender and racial bias as negatively impacting the client experience for persons with coronary and peripheral artery disease. The chat covers not only cardiovascular health, but also technologies that may be utilized to bridge the critical gaps identified.
        </para>
        <para id="para-00018">
          <emphasis effect="italics">Sources [ipsum lorum text]: Leek, J. C. &amp; Arif, H. (2022) Pregnancy medications. National Library of Medicine: National Center for biotechnology Information. Lopez, E. O., Parmar, M., Pendela, V. S., &amp; Terrell, J. M. (2022) Lisinopril. National Library of Medicine. Luehrs, R. E., Zhang, D., Pierce, G.L., Jacobs Jr., D. R., Kalhan, R., &amp; Whitaker, K. (2021). Cigarette smoking and longitudinal associations with blood pressure: The CARDIA study. Journal of the American Heart Association. 10(9). https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/full/10.1161/JAHA.120.019566</emphasis>
        </para>
      </note>
      <section id="sect-00006">
        <title>Dietary Modification</title>
        <para id="para-00019">
          Clients with hypertension should eat a low-sodium diet consisting of whole grains, vegetables, and fruits. Other recommendations include low-fat dairy products and limiting meat intake to a total of 6 ounces of lean meat, such as fish and poultry, daily. Reducing sweets and red meat is also important. The American Heart Association (2022) recommends 1500 mg to no more than 2300 mg of sodium intake per day. Dietary pattern and nutritional therapy should focus on food preference, social and cultural influences, and appropriate caloric intake.
        </para>
      </section>
      <section id="sect-00007">
        <title>Physical Activity and Exercise</title>
        <para id="para-00020">
          Moderate exercise is recommended by the American Heart Association (2022) at least four times a week for adults. Average time for exercise should be at least 30–40 minutes per session to assist in decreasing blood pressure. If the client cannot do 30–40 minutes of moderate exercise four times a week, suggest an alternate exercise plan, emphasizing that some physical activity is better than no physical activity. Physical activity and exercise enhance weight reduction and promote a healthy lifestyle. A weight reduction of at least 10 kg can reduce blood pressure by 5 to 20 mm Hg (Ghadieh, 2015).
        </para>
      </section>
      <section id="sect-00008">
        <title>Smoking Cessation and Reducing Alcohol Consumption</title>
        <para id="para-00021">
          Tobacco use is the leading preventable cause of coronary artery disease. Smoking increases sympathetic nervous system activity, and therefore increases blood pressure, heart rate, and myocardial contractility. Smoking cessation can decrease the risk of coronary artery disease by more than 30% (Luehrs et al., 2021).
        </para>
        <para id="para-00022">
          Alcohol consumption increases blood pressure by increasing the level of the hormone renin in the blood. Renin decreases fluid elimination and leads to higher fluid volume in the body, which therefore increases blood pressure. A reduction of alcohol consumption has been shown to decrease both systolic and/or diastolic blood pressure by 5 to 12 mm Hg (Wake, 2021).
        </para>
      </section>
      <section id="sect-00009">
        <title>Relaxation Techniques</title>
        <para id="para-00023">
          Relaxation techniques can include mindfulness-based stress reduction, transcendental meditation, deep breathing exercises, stretching, tai chi, yoga, and acupuncture. These techniques have been shown to decrease autonomic nervous system activity and lower stress and blood pressure (Brook et al., 2013).
        </para>
        <note class="clinical-tip" id="note-00003">
          <title>Assessing Client Lifestyle Modifications</title>
          <para id="para-00024">
            Monitor the client closely for lifestyle changes that will improve baseline blood pressure readings such as diet modifications and weight loss, exercise, smoking cessation, and relaxation.
          </para>
        </note>
      </section>
      <section id="sect-00010">
        <title>Self-Monitoring of Hypertension</title>
        <para id="para-00025">
          Home blood pressure monitoring (<link target-id="pharma_fig_18_01_003"/>) is essential in lowering blood pressure. Clients are now able to monitor their blood pressure with electronic blood pressure devices. Home blood pressure monitoring leads to awareness of one’s blood pressure, better blood pressure control, and adherence to lifestyle changes and drug therapies (Verma et al., 2021).
        </para>
