      </section>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00011">
      <title>Pharmacologic Treatment of Hypertension</title>
      <para id="para-00026">Pharmacologic treatment for hypertension centers on the individual client and takes into consideration their lifestyle as well as their personal, social, and cultural preferences. The objectives of pharmacological treatment are to reduce blood pressure and reduce the long-term effects of hypertension on the body, such as organ damage. The primary antihypertensive drugs used to treat high blood pressure include angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors, angiotensin II receptor blockers, beta-adrenergic blockers, calcium channel blockers, and diuretics. These drugs will be discussed further in this chapter.
      </para>
      <note class="clinical-tip" id="note-00004">
        <title>Assessing Therapeutic Effects</title>
        <para id="para-00027">Monitor the client’s blood pressure to assess for drug efficacy. If the blood pressure remains elevated despite antihypertensive treatment, the healthcare provider may adjust antihypertensive drugs to better control the client’s blood pressure.</para>
      </note>
    </section>
  </section>
    <section id="sect-00012">
      <title>Angina</title>
      <para id="para-00028">
        <term id="term-00016">Angina</term> (also called angina pectoris) is defined as discomfort in the front of the chest, neck, shoulders, jaw, or arms that is precipitated by physical exertions and relieved by rest or sublingual nitrates (Timmis &amp; Roobottom, 2015). Angina is caused by reduced blood flow to the heart. There are four types of angina (Mayo, 2022):
        <list list-type="bulleted" id="list-00002">
          <item>Stable angina is the most common form. It occurs during activity and goes away with rest. Stable angina is predictable and follows a pattern similar to the previous episodes of chest pain.</item>
          <item>Unstable angina is unpredictable and considered a medical emergency. Unlike stable angina, it does not follow a pattern similar to previous episodes of chest pain, and episodes last longer than stable angina episodes. If blood flow to the heart doesn’t improve, a myocardial infarction (heart attack) may occur.</item>
          <item>Variant (Prinzmetal) angina is caused by a spasm in the hearts arteries and can occur at rest. This type of angina often occurs in cycles, and may occur at rest or overnight.</item>
          <item>Refractory angina is frequent episodes of angina that occur despite lifestyle changes and medication.</item>
        </list>
        Risk factors for angina include age, family history, tobacco use, diabetes, hypertension, high cholesterol, obesity, emotional stress, and drug misuse (Mayo, 2022).
      </para>
      <section id="sect-00013">
        <title>Pharmacologic Treatment of Angina</title>
        <para id="para-00029">
          Pharmacologic treatment for angina is individualized. Client lifestyle as well as social and cultural influences impact the health care provider’s choice of drug. The goal for pharmacologic treatment of stable angina is to prevent an ischemic event, such as myocardial ischemia (heart attack), from occurring. Nitrates are the first line of treatment for angina, along with beta-adrenergic blockers and calcium channel blockers (Rousan &amp; Thadani, 2019). These drugs will be discussed further in this chapter.
        </para>
      </section>
    
<note class="client-teaching" id="note-00005">
  <title>Antihypertensive/Antianginal Use</title>
  <para id="para-00030"><emphasis effect="bold">The client should:</emphasis>
  <list list-type="bulleted" id="list-00003">
    <item>Take antihypertensive and antianginal drugs as prescribed by their health care provider.</item>
    <item>Take their blood pressure and pulse prior to starting an antihypertensive drug, to obtain a baseline reading.</item>
    <item>Monitor their blood pressure and pulse regularly or as directed by their health care provider and keep a record of the reading for the healthcare provider. The client should report significant changes to their health care provider.</item>
    <item>Keep a record of the number and severity of angina episodes to review with their healthcare provider.</item>
    <item>Keep family and support system informed of emergency use of antianginal drugs and their location.</item>
    <item>Wear a medical alert bracelet and carry a list of drugs they are currently taking. </item>
    <item>Avoid alcohol, caffeine, and tobacco because these may interfere with the action of antihypertensive and antianginal drugs.</item>
  </list>
  </para>
  <para id="para-00031"><emphasis effect="bold">The client <emphasis effect="italics">should not</emphasis>:</emphasis>
    <list list-type="bulleted" id="list-00004">
      <item>Take a double dose of the antihypertensive drug. If the client misses a dose of their antihypertensive drug, they should take it as soon as they remember—unless it’s almost time for the next dose. In that case, they should wait and take the next dose at the normal time.</item>
      <item>Abruptly discontinue an antihypertensive drug without consulting with the health care provider, because with some drugs this may cause rebound elevated blood pressure and an elevated pulse rate.</item>
      <item>Take over the counter (OTC) drugs and/or herbal supplements without consulting with their health care provider or pharmacist.</item>
    </list>
    </para>
    <para id="para-00032"><emphasis effect="bold">Other concerns:</emphasis>
      <list list-type="bulleted" id="list-00005">
        <item>Headaches may occur with the use of nitrates. Acetaminophen may help in relieving these headaches.</item>
        <item>Antihypertensive drugs may cause orthostatic hypotension (a form of low blood pressure that occurs when going from a sitting or lying position to a standing position). The client should change positions slowly to prevent dizziness and fainting.</item>
        <item>If low blood pressure develops (feeling dizzy or lightheaded, having blurred vision, feeling weak, or fainting), the client should lie on their back with legs elevated and notify their health care provider.</item>
        <item>If the client is unsure about how to take their antihypertensive drug, they should call their health care provider or pharmacist.</item>
        </list>
      </para>
</note>
